## User Auth (project-scoped, for your app's end-users)

Each project has its own user table (`project_users`). Sign-up and login are scoped to the
project — a user registered in project 5 cannot log into project 6.
The returned JWT carries a `pid` claim that ties it to this project.

### Sign up
```bash
curl -s -X POST "$SUPABEIN_URL/api/v1/projects/$SUPABEIN_PROJECT_ID/auth/signup" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"email":"user@example.com","password":"secret123"}'
# returns { token: "eyJ..." }
```

### Log in
```bash
curl -s -X POST "$SUPABEIN_URL/api/v1/projects/$SUPABEIN_PROJECT_ID/auth/login" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"email":"user@example.com","password":"secret123"}'
# returns { token: "eyJ..." }
```

### Get current user
```bash
curl -s "$SUPABEIN_URL/api/v1/projects/$SUPABEIN_PROJECT_ID/auth/me" \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $USER_TOKEN"
# returns { id: 1, email: "...", created_at: "..." }
```

### Refresh token
```bash
curl -s -X POST "$SUPABEIN_URL/api/v1/projects/$SUPABEIN_PROJECT_ID/auth/refresh" \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $USER_TOKEN"
# returns { token: "eyJ..." } — fresh expiry, same user
```

Use the returned JWT as `Authorization: Bearer <token>` for authenticated data API calls.
The JWT is scoped to this project and will be rejected by other projects' data endpoints.

